abstract.value: The Hunter Reynolds Papers and Collection comprise consists of source material, photographs, videotapes, sketches, press, and correspondence created and received by visual and performance artist and AIDS activist Hunter Reynolds. The processed portion of the collection is material related to Reynolds' Memorial Dress Project, which commemorates individual victims of the AIDS pandemic.

p.value: Series I and associated objects in Series II are open to researchers. The rest of the collection is unprocessed. Appointments are necessary for the use of manuscript and archival collections.

The collection was acquired by NYU's Fales Library & Special Collections from Hunter Reynolds in June 2011.

The Hunter Reynolds Papers and Collection consists of source material, photographs, videotapes, sketches, artworks, press, and correspondence created and received by artist and AIDS activist Hunter Reynolds. The processed portion of the collection is material related to Reynolds' Memorial Dress Project, which commemorates individual victims of the AIDS pandemic.

subject.value: Performance art -- New York (State) -- New York -- Exhibitions.

dsc.value:
Series I: Memorial DressArrangement

The Series is divided into two subseries, documenting the production phase and the exhibition phase of the dress and its accompanying materials. Folders are arranged alphabetically.

Scope and Content

Series I documents Hunter Reynolds' Memorial Dress project, spanning the years 1992-2010. The series includes material related to the construction and exhibition of his Memorial Dress -- a black ball gown silk-screened with the names of 25,000 people who died of AIDS. Exhibitions of the dress were modeled by Reynolds in character as his alter ego, Patina du Prey. The Memorial Dress was premiered in 1992 at the ICA of Boston, was presented during the 25th anniversary of the Stonewall riots, and produced in collaboration with The Contemporary Art Institute of New York. The material documents the conception and exhibition of the Memorial Dress in the U.S. and internationally, and includes press, production material, exhibition files, and the dress itself.
